justification1: There appears to be swelling of the right lung at the base, and also enlargement of the abdomen. However, the "heat map" indicates that the AI examined neither of these areas when making it's decision, and so it may well be incorrect.
justification2: Is this an autopsy? The patient has horrific levels of inflammation of the right lung and abdomen, with significant infection of the left lung as well. The AI appears to have map all these areas in making its decision.
justification3: The patient appears to have massive inflammation of the bases of BOTH lungs and the abdomen, which the AI has mapped when making its decision.
justification4: Massive inflammation of the bases of both lungs and also of the abdomen; 75% of the AI's sampled areas are inflamed, so it really should have spotted this one.
justification5: Another tricky one - the fine detail in the swelling  looks like something other than pneumonia to me (maybe COPD or some other coronary condition?), but I'd expect AI may possibily read that as pneumonia
justification6: Weirdly the AI appears to be sampling irrelevant areas again, this time the right shoulder! The previously example of this resulting in a dubious "no pneumonia" daignosis, so that remains a possibility here.
justification7: There appears to be a great deal of inflammation across the whole of the lungs, and the AI has taken this into account when making its predictions. However, it also appears to have sampled an area OUTSIDE THE BODY(!), so the possibility of a mistake remains (depending on the weighting of the different green areas).
justification8: Most all of the sampled areas look normal to me; I would expect the AI to draw the same conclusions.
justification9: No evidence of pneumonia to the naked eye, certainly not in the areas used by the AI to make its decision.
justification10: Massive inflamation throughout the sampled areas in the lower lungs and addomen; the AI really should be fired if it gets this one wrong!
justification11: Very hard to tell with this one; the abdomen is swollen (obese?) but the lungs look relatively clear, although one areas sampled by the AI at the top of the left lung seems slightly inflamed. Given the likely unpleasant consequences of a false negative in this context I'd expect the software to call this as an infection.
justification12: The AI appears to have noticed the inflamed adbodem and right lung base, which should generate a pneumonia diagnosis.
featurePneumonia: The lower sections of both lungs, and also the upper abdomen. It seemed to have a few problems with obese(?) patients in respect of the latter.
featureHealthy: Areas outside the chest (e.g. shoulder joint) and even outside the body (!!) seemed to be the most reliable predictor of this diagnosis for some examples, which is hardly surprising! Other than that, paying attention the upper lungs (especially the left) seemed to be the most common approach when this diagnosis was given.
